d Faith: The IMF and Europe on Greece -- tTwenty-Five. Only the "No" Can Save the Euro -- tTwenty-Six. Nine Myths About the Greek Referendum -- tTwenty-Seven. What Is the Matter with Europe? -- tTwenty-Eight. Exit Made Easy -- tTwenty-Nine. Greece, Europe, and the United States -- tThirty. Plan B -- tThirty-One. Statement on the Ministry of Finance Working Group -- tThirty-Two. A Note to the Editors at the Guardian -- tThirty-Three. Death Spiral Ahead? -- tThirty-Four. The Future of Europe -- tThirty-Five. What the Greek Memorandum Means / rMunevar, Daniel -- tThirty-Six. Back to Square Zero -- tThirty-Seven. A Final Word: Madrid, October 21, 2015 -- tAppendix: A Summary of Plan X -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA world-renowned economist offers cogent and powerful reflections on one of the great avoidable economic catastrophes of the modern era The economic crisis in Greece is a potential international disaster and one of the most extraordinary monetary and political dramas of our time. The financial woes of this relatively small European nation threaten the long-term viability of the Euro while exposing the flaws in the ideal of continental unity. ";Solutions"; proposed by Europe's combined leadership have sparked a war of prideful words and stubborn one-upmanship, and they are certain to fail, according to renowned economist James K. Galbraith, because they are designed for failure. It is this hypocrisy that prompted former finance minister Yanis Varoufakis, when Galbraith arrived in Athens as an adviser, to greet him with the words "Welcome to the poisoned chalice."   In this fascinating, insightful, and thought-provoking collection of essays-which includes letters and private memos to both American and Greek officials, as well as other previously unpublished material-Galbraith examines the crisis, its causes, its course, and its meaning, as well as the viability of the austerity program imposed on the Greek citizenry. It is a trenchant, deeply felt commentary on what the author calls "economic policy as moral abomination," and an eye-opening analysis of a contemporary Greek tragedy much greater than the tiny economy of the nation itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Feb 2020) 7aHISTORY / Modern / 21st Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYUP eBook-Package 2016z978311066771440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300224221423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780300224221.jpg  a978-3-11-066771-4  YUP eBook-Package 2016b2016  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aEBA_FAO